03870nam a22004935i 9781847421159DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847421159  a(DE-B1597)646112  a(OCoLC)1371574505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a363.73/209411 aSmith, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRethinking residential child care :bPositive perspectives /cMark Smith. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tThe context of care -- tHistory -- tInquiries and their impact -- tTrends and policy directions -- tTheorising residential child care -- tThe residential environment -- tAssessment, care planning and programming -- tWorking at the boundaries: the personal–professional relationship -- tResidential child care in a continuum of care -- tOther traditions of practice -- tConclusion: rethinking residential child care -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aResidential child care is a crucial, though relatively neglected area of social work. And yet, revelations of abuse and questions of effectiveness have led to increasingly regulatory and procedural approaches to practice and heightened political and professional scrutiny. This book provides a broad and critical look at the ideas and policy developments that have shaped the direction of the sector. The book sets present-day policy and practice within historical, policy and organisational context. The author applies a critical gaze to attempts to improve practice through regulation and, fundamentally, challenges how residential child care is conceptualised. He argues that it needs to move beyond dominant discourses of protection, rights and outcomes to embrace those of care and upbringing. The importance of the personal relationship in helping children to grow and develop is highlighted. Other traditions of practice such as the European concept of social pedagogy are also explored to more accurately reflect the task of residential child care. The book will be of interest to practitioners in residential child care, social workers and students on social work and social care courses. It should be required reading for social work managers and will also be of interest to policy makers and students of social policy, education and childhood studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildrenxInstitutional care. 0aSocial work with children. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aFulcher, Leon C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978186134908840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847421159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847421159/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles